Second.

309
00:23:48,357 --> 00:23:51,357
Yes, you just, if you can just come a little closer so we can.

310
00:23:55,198 --> 00:24:01,440
I'm old school, and I went to the old school that was finished off in 1970.

311
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:04,120
This was started in 1971, I believe.

312
00:24:05,321 --> 00:24:08,201
And it seems like it's like 56 years old.

313
00:24:09,102 --> 00:24:13,663
I'm thinking, this brick and mortar building looks pretty damn good outside.

314
00:24:14,563 --> 00:24:21,905
And with all the leaks we've got since 1971, we're not even one year old, and the contractor never came back.

315
00:24:22,465 --> 00:24:23,365
We're always notified.

316
00:24:23,821 --> 00:24:24,441
repeatedly.

317
00:24:27,022 --> 00:24:37,947
So I think old school, and you're going to change flat roofs like maybe 10, 15, 20 years, whenever the old timer comes up to inspect for you, instead of a knock, et cetera.

318
00:24:39,388 --> 00:24:44,790
In my opinion, so it looks pretty solid out there.

319
00:24:45,791 --> 00:24:50,293
And the old high school, I got out of that one, 68, 11 years.

320
00:24:53,335 --> 00:24:53,835
Anyways.

321
00:24:54,815 --> 00:24:56,376
Did you have a comment about the mailer?

322
00:24:57,676 --> 00:24:58,496
No, that's the subject?

323
00:24:58,556 --> 00:24:58,816
Yes.

324
00:24:59,456 --> 00:25:02,637
Well, I'm worried about spending hundreds of millions of dollars.

325
00:25:03,257 --> 00:25:05,897
This is my first time here and probably my last.

326
00:25:06,537 --> 00:25:10,018
But I want to say the old high school is going to be standing like the Coliseum in Rome.

327
00:25:10,198 --> 00:25:14,419
And when I went there, we were on a split session after we started in 1965.

328
00:25:15,939 --> 00:25:18,379
And we went to two buildings that were open.

329
00:25:18,399 --> 00:25:20,460
And we had a plywood hallway.

330
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:22,840
And the center building was bright, and the one in the rear

331
00:25:23,931 --> 00:25:25,492
The location was burned.

332
00:25:25,512 --> 00:25:27,353
It was a vicious fire.

333
00:25:28,294 --> 00:25:35,539
And I would think we would be like six, seven years on split sections of eight to 12 and one to five.

334
00:25:36,140 --> 00:25:47,508
Why couldn't they have built those two wings that were burned and then switched the other way and remodeled the other two wings that we were using?

335
00:25:49,429 --> 00:25:49,890
I don't know.

336
00:25:50,850 --> 00:25:52,572
There were 8,000 homes in this city.

337
00:25:54,680 --> 00:25:55,340
100 years old.

338
00:25:55,741 --> 00:25:59,282
And these immigrants with two rolls in our paycheck, if they made $2.50.

339
00:26:00,223 --> 00:26:03,344
These old homes are still standing.

340
00:26:04,645 --> 00:26:05,465
Thank you for listening.

341
00:26:05,925 --> 00:26:06,325
Thank you.

342
00:26:06,345 --> 00:26:08,826
Is there a second?

343
